On 8/8/19 7:31 AM, Theodore Y. Ts'o wrote:
> I implemented loading the root file system as a ramdisk from a=20
> floppy in 1991 for Linux.

Impressive.

> This predates the publication of 386BSD, and I wasn't aware of how=20
> commercial Unix systems did their initial installation and setup.=20
> So as far as I know I came up on it on my own, but none of this was=20
> especially earthshaking or subtle.

That logic makes sense to me.

> Linux's ramdisk was implemented because most PC's of the day (I was=20
> using a 40 MHz 386 with only a megabyte of memory) only had a single=20
> floppy drive (and if they had a second it was a 5.25" drive).  So the=20
> very first implementation which I did assumed the kernel would be no=20
> larger than 512k, and looked for Minix file system signature at 512k.=20
> If it existed, it would load it into the ramdisk and use that as the=20
> boot region.

That's before my time.  If I remember correctly, by the time I was=20
creating boot+root disks it was the kernel plus something=E2=80=94I don't=
=20
remember if it was an initramfs or an initrd=E2=80=94concatenated togethe=
r.  I=20
also remember having to use a utility to update the kernel to tell it=20
where the something started.  Which was really based on how big the=20
kernel was as padding before the something started.  That was probably=20
2.<something> on Slackware in '99.

> Before that, the kernel was loaded from the first floppy, and then=20
> kernel would prompt the user to eject the boot disk and insert the=20
> root disk, and hit any key to continue, and then it would mount the=20
> root disk.

I remember doing that.  But perhaps it was for a different reason.

> But then the only floppy drive would be tied up with the root file=20
> system, so that meant there needed to be a second kernel on the root=20
> floppy, and everything else needed to set up the root image would=20
> have to be copied to the hard disk, and then you'd have to reboot=20
> to release the floppy drive so you could install other programs that=20
> couldn't fit on that initial 1.44MB root floppy.
>=20
> For people who are interested in the history of initrd used as part=20
> of the boot process in Linux, please refer to Werner Almesberger's=20
> 2000 paper, "Booting Linux: The History and the Future"[1], presented=20
> at the Ottawa Linux Symposium.
>=20
> [1] http://www.almesberger.net/cv/papers/ols2k-9.ps.gz

I will definitely check that out.  Thank you for the link.

> Cheers,

